ture is **dramatically more constrained** than Amazon\'s was in FY2025. Amazon\'s total capex still left positive free cash flow. SpaceX\'s AI capex alone — excluding Space segment capex ($3,832M in FY2025) and Connectivity\'s own sustaining capex ($4,178M in FY2025) — exceeds the Connectivity segment\'s entire Adjusted EBITDA by a factor of more than four.\n\n**Reinforcing consolidated view:** On a fully consolidated basis, SpaceX FY2025 total capex ($20,737M) was **306%** of consolidated OCF ($6,785M). The Q1 2026 annualized run rate implies consolidated capex of $40,428M against annualized OCF of only $4,188M — a ratio of **965%**. Amazon\'s consolidated ratio of 92–94% is an order of magnitude lower.\n\n---\n\n### 4. Disclosures Provided vs. Omitted — Factors Limiting Confidence\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 provides sufficient data to perform the calculation above, but several critical disclosures are absent, materially limiting the reliability of any direct comparison with Amazon:\n\n#### (a) No Segment-Level Cash Flow\nThe S-1 provides Segment Adjusted EBITDA (a non-GAAP profit proxy) for each segment but **no segment-level statement of cash flows** and **no reconciliation from Segment Adjusted EBITDA to segment operating cash flow**. Amazon\'s denominator is GAAP operating cash flow; SpaceX\'s denominator is a non-GAAP measure that excludes depreciation, amortization, share-based compensation, restructuring, and impairments — some of which have real cash implications. The translation from Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA to actual cash available for cross-segment deployment is undisclosed and uncertain.\n\n#### (b) Connectivity\'s Own Capital Requirements Are Not Netted\nConnectivity itself consumed $4,178M in capex during FY2025 and $1,332M in Q1 2026. If Connectivity\'s Adj EBITDA must first cover its own capex before any surplus is available for AI, the residual is only $7,168M – $4,178M = **$2,990M** (FY2025). Using this as the denominator yields a pressure ratio of **$30,892M ÷ $2,990M = 10.33 (1,033%)** — more than double the already extreme 431%. The filing does not disclose what portion of Connectivity\'s cash generation is retained within the segment versus made available for corporate allocation.\n\n#### (c) No Cross-Segment Funding Policy Disclosed\nThe S-1 describes historical capital flows (Space funded Connectivity) and explicitly states that AI will be funded through **external debt and equity markets**, not internal cash:\n> *"We plan to access a range of debt and equity financing solutions available to us as a public company to fund future investments in growth..."*\n\nThe filing does **not** state that Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA is, or will be, the primary funding source for AI capex. The "primary internal cash source" characterization is an inference — one the company\'s own disclosures appear to deprecate by emphasizing external financing for AI.\n\n#### (d) AI Capex Run Rate May Not Be Stable\nAnnualizing a single quarter (Q1 2026) assumes linear spending. The S-1 shows construction-in-progress surging from $4,604M to $14,045M in Q1 2026 alone, contractual commitments of $25.5B (with $21.5B due in 2027), and forward-looking language that capex "will scale as quickly as we are able to deploy power and compute." The Q1 2026 run rate may understate rather than overstate future spending.\n\n#### (e) Numerator/Denominator Mismatch\nAmazon\'s ratio uses **total** consolidated capex and **total** consolidated OCF — like measured against like, on the same GAAP basis. The SpaceX ratio pairs **one segment\'s capex** (AI) against **a different segment\'s non-GAAP profit metric** (Connectivity). This cross-segment, cross-metric construction has no direct GAAP analogue and is inherently less rigorous than Amazon\'s like-for-like comparison.\n\n#### (f) Consolidated OCF Masks Segment Composition\nSpaceX\'s consolidated OCF of $6,785M (FY2025) reflects the net of all three segments plus corporate-level items. The Connectivity segment\'s contribution to consolidated OCF cannot be isolated from the financial statements. If a material portion of consolidated OCF derives from non-Connectivity sources (e.g., customer prepayments in Space, working capital), then Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA overstates Connectivity\'s actual cash contribution.\n\n#### (g) Post-Merger Recast Financials\nAll historical financials reflect the retrospective common-control combination of SpaceX, xAI, and X Holdings. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations. The Connectivity segment\'s historical Adj EBITDA trajectory may embed recast adjustments whose nature is not fully transparent, potentially affecting trend analysis.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Dimension | Amazon FY2025 | SpaceX (Analogous) |\n|:---|:---|:---|\n| Ratio | ~94% (capex within OCF) | ~431% (AI capex alone 4.3× Connectivity Adj EBITDA) |\n| Internal funding position | Constrained but cash-flow-positive | Severely constrained; AI capex dwarfs internal cash generation |\n| Key disclosure strength | GAAP OCF and capex on same consolidated basis | Transparent segment Adj EBITDA and segment capex |\n| Key disclosure gap | N/A | No segment cash flow; no cross-segment funding policy; reliance on non-GAAP proxy; external financing emphasized over internal funding |\n\nThe S-1 makes clear that SpaceX\'s AI build-out will be funded predominantly through external capital markets, not internal cash generation — a fact that the ratio calculation above corroborates by demonstrating that internal sources are quantitatively insufficient to cover the AI spending trajectory.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n- SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\n- Amazon 10-K (FY2025, filed Feb 6, 2026): https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1018724/000101872426000004/amzn-20251231.htm',
